Project Architecture Overview (Your Actual Experience Explained Simply)

My current project follows a modern microservices-based architecture hosted entirely on Azure, with a strong focus on AKS, DevOps automation, security, monitoring, and integration services.

ğŸ— High-Level Architecture
1. Frontend & Global Routing Layer

Azure Front Door (AFD) for global routing, caching, WAF policies, and TLS termination

Routes traffic to backend Azure regions based on:

Latency

Path rules (API vs UI)

Health probes

AFD protects the system from malicious requests using custom WAF rules

2. Application Hosting Layer

Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS)

Multiple node pools (system & user)

Ingress Controller (NGINX/AGIC) for routing inside the cluster

HPA for auto-scaling

Pod-level security, readiness/liveness probes

Helm charts for deployments

Azure App Services

Used for specific admin/utility tools

Connected to private endpoints for secure access

3. Data & Storage Layer

Azure SQL Database

For transactional data

Private endpoint + firewall restrictions

Azure Cosmos DB

For semi-structured data and telemetry

Azure Storage Accounts (Blob, Queue, File)

Blob for media & logs

Queues for async processing

Files for legacy data ingestion and log archival

4. Integration & Eventing Layer

Azure Service Bus (Topics & Queues)

Handles async communication between microservices

Dead-letter queues monitored with alerts

Azure Functions

Event-driven background processing

Connected through Service Bus triggers and Event Grid

APIs

API layer deployed in AKS

Secured with Managed Identity and Key Vault

5. Security Layer

Azure Key Vault

Stores secrets, certificates, and connection strings

Accessed using Managed Identities (no plain-text secrets)

Network Security Groups (NSGs)

Protect subnets & VM access

Azure Firewall & UDRs

Centrally control outbound traffic

Forced tunneling for restricted resources

Private Endpoints

For SQL, Storage, Key Vault, Service Busâ€”all traffic stays inside Microsoft backbone

AAD Integration

RBAC for pipelines, service principals, managed identities

6. Monitoring & Observability Layer

Azure Monitor + Log Analytics

Custom KQL alerts for API failures, CPU spikes, Pod memory usage

Application Insights

End-to-end request tracking

Distributed tracing for microservices

Container Insights

Node, pod, and container-level metrics

Azure Alerts â†’ Teams/Email

Threshold-based alerts

Query-based alerts for recurring log patterns (e.g., authentication failures)

7. DevOps Layer

Azure DevOps Repos

Mono-repo or microservice repos

Azure DevOps YAML Pipelines

CI â†’ Build + image push to ACR

CD â†’ Helm-based AKS deployments

Variable groups for secrets

Environment-specific approvals

Terraform

IaC for AKS, SQL, Service Bus, Storage, Networking

Remote backend using Azure Storage + Key for locking

ACR (Azure Container Registry)

Stores container images

Connected to AKS with managed identity

ğŸš€ Summary (Use this in interview to sound confident and structured)

â€œOur architecture is fully built on Azure using a microservices model. We use Azure Front Door for global routing and WAF, AKS as the primary 
compute layer with Helm-based deployments, and Azure SQL + Cosmos DB for data. We rely heavily on Service Bus for asynchronous communication and 
use Key Vault, private endpoints, NSGs, and Azure Firewall for security. The entire estate is monitored using Azure Monitor, Log Analytics, and 
Application Insights. All deployments are automated using Azure DevOps YAML pipelines and Terraform for infrastructure provisioning.â€

